Training & Test Sets

  • Data Fit: Fit model to training period . We aim to estimate the model parameters.
  • Predictive Accuracy: Assess performance on test period. We aim to check the performance of the forecasting method.
  • Deploy model by joining training + validation to forecast future.

Data Example

  • Back in 2001, a store wanted to use the data to forecast sales for the next 12 months (year 2002).

  • They hired an analyst to generate forecasts. The analyst first partitioned the data into training and validation periods, with the validation period containing the last 12 months of data (year 2001).

  • She/he then fit a forecasting model to sales, using the training period.

Data Example (cont’d)

Souvenir Sales: The file SouvenirSales.xls contains monthly sales for a souvenir shop at a beach resort town in Queensland, Australia, between 1995 and 2001.

Naïve Model

  • Forecasts equal to last observed value.
  • Forecasts: \(\hat{y}_{T+h|T} =y_T\).
  • Perform a naïve forecast method with the naive function.
  • We can print off the model summary with summary, which provides us with the residual standard deviation, some error measures (which we will cover later), and the actual forecasted values.
 # Naïve Model
library(forecast)
naive.model<-naive(train.ts, 12)
summary(naive.model)

Seasonal Naïve Model

  • Forecasts equal to last value from same season.
  • Forecasts: \(\hat{y}_{T+h|T} =y_{T+h-m(k+1)}\), where \(m=\) seasonal period and \(k\) is the integer part of \((h-1)/m\).
  • Perform a seasonal naïve forecast method with the snaive function.
 # Seasonal Naïve Model
library(forecast)
snaive.model<-snaive(train.ts, 12)
snaive.model

Assessing Residuals

When applying a forecasting method, it is important to always check that the residuals are well-behaved (i.e., no outliers or patterns) and resemble white noise.

  • Essential assumptions for an appropriate forecasting model include residuals being:

    • Uncorrelated
    • Centered at mean zero

  • Furthermore, the prediction intervals are computed assuming that the residuals:

    • Have constant variance
    • Are normally distributed

Assessing Residuals (cont’d)

  • Naïve model

    • Not “white noise” (we see some patterns)
    • Not constant variance
    • Normally distributed
    • Centered at mean zero
# measuring forecast accuracy
checkresiduals(naive.model)

## 
##  Ljung-Box test
## 
## data:  Residuals from Naive method
## Q* = 62.944, df = 14, p-value = 3.551e-08
## 
## Model df: 0.   Total lags used: 14

Assessing Residuals (cont’d)

  • Seasonal Naïve model

    • Not “white noise” (we see some patterns)
    • Not constant variance
    • Normally distributed
    • centered at mean zero
# measuring forecast accuracy
checkresiduals(snaive.model)

## 
##  Ljung-Box test
## 
## data:  Residuals from Seasonal naive method
## Q* = 30.971, df = 14, p-value = 0.005596
## 
## Model df: 0.   Total lags used: 14

Forecast Accuracy Measures

  • Commonly used to assess the predictive accuracy of a forecasting method

  • The measures are based on the test data set, which serves as a more objective basis than the training period to assess predictive accuracy

Forecast Accuracy Measures (cont’d)

Perdicition Intervals

  • A prediction interval gives an interval within which we expect to lie with a specified probability.
  • Allows us to understand the uncertainty that exists in a forecast.
  • Should always report \(\color{red}{\text{point estimate}}\) and \(\color{red}{\text{prediction intervals}}\) for forecasts.
  • It is common to calculate 80% intervals and 95% intervals, although any percentage may be used.

Data Example (cont’d): Prediction Intervals

  • Naïve Model
  • Blue line represents point estimates, which are equal to the last observed value (It’s a flat line).
  • Colored bands represent our 80% and 95% prediction confidence interval.
 #  Naïve Model
autoplot(naive.model)
